{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Artificial intelligence uses data, algorithms, and computing power to recognize patterns, generate content, and support decisions. See where AI appears in daily life, why its limits matter, and how people apply it in science, business, art, and public life.",
    "title": "How artificial intelligence works in the world"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "AI systems turn examples into models that can classify images, predict outcomes, recommend choices, or create new text and pictures. Their abilities come from learned patterns rather than humanlike common sense.",
      "title": "How artificial intelligence learns from patterns"
    },
    {
      "description": "A model can produce a fluent answer without knowing whether it is true. This gap explains surprising AI mistakes and makes testing, reliable data, and human judgment essential.",
      "title": "Why artificial intelligence can sound right and be wrong"
    },
    {
      "description": "Search results, navigation, spam filters, medical imaging, fraud alerts, and streaming recommendations all use AI. Each application balances usefulness with costs such as errors, privacy risks, and unfair outcomes.",
      "title": "Where artificial intelligence shapes daily decisions"
    },
    {
      "description": "Generative AI predicts and combines patterns to produce text, images, audio, video, and code. Questions about training data, originality, accuracy, and authorship connect the technology to culture and creative work.",
      "title": "How generative AI creates text, images, and code"
    },
    {
      "description": "Researchers, engineers, designers, data specialists, policy experts, and domain professionals build and evaluate AI systems. Their projects range from scientific discovery and accessibility tools to robotics, language technology, and responsible AI governance.",
      "title": "What people build and study with artificial intelligence"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Dos micróbios ao corpo humano e às florestas, a biologia investiga como a vida funciona, muda e se conecta. Suas ideias ajudam a cuidar da saúde, produzir alimentos, conservar espécies e criar novas tecnologias.",
    "title": "Biologia: a ciência da vida"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "A biologia busca responder perguntas concretas: o que define um ser vivo, como os organismos obtêm energia, por que envelhecem e como novas espécies surgem. Ela conecta observações de moléculas, organismos e ambientes inteiros.",
      "title": "O que a biologia investiga"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cada ser vivo é formado por uma ou mais células, capazes de usar energia, produzir componentes e responder ao ambiente. Até tarefas comuns, como cicatrizar um corte ou digerir uma refeição, dependem da atividade coordenada dessas pequenas unidades.",
      "title": "Como as células mantêm a vida funcionando"
    },
    {
      "description": "O DNA guarda instruções biológicas usando combinações de apenas quatro componentes químicos. Mudanças nessas instruções ajudam a explicar características herdadas, doenças genéticas, evolução e até como parentescos podem ser identificados.",
      "title": "DNA: um alfabeto compartilhado pela vida"
    },
    {
      "description": "Nenhuma espécie vive isolada: plantas, animais, fungos, micróbios, água e clima formam redes de dependência. Essas relações explicam fenômenos como polinização, decomposição, equilíbrio de populações e impactos ambientais.",
      "title": "Como a ecologia conecta espécies e ambientes"
    },
    {
      "description": "Biólogos atuam em laboratórios, hospitais, áreas de conservação, escolas, empresas, museus e órgãos públicos. Eles podem monitorar animais, analisar microrganismos, desenvolver produtos, investigar doenças ou restaurar ecossistemas.",
      "title": "O que biólogos fazem no mundo real"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Quantum mechanics describes matter and light at atomic scales, where probabilities replace precise predictions and particles can behave like waves. Its ideas explain chemistry, lasers, computer chips, medical imaging, and emerging quantum technologies.",
    "title": "The strange and useful quantum world"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Quantum mechanics studies atoms, electrons, photons, and other tiny systems. Instead of assigning every property a definite value, it predicts the probabilities of possible measurement results with extraordinary accuracy.",
      "title": "What quantum mechanics describes"
    },
    {
      "description": "A quantum object can occupy a combination of possible states called a superposition. Interference between these possibilities produces patterns that have no classical counterpart and makes quantum behavior both surprising and useful.",
      "title": "Superposition and quantum possibilities"
    },
    {
      "description": "Measurement is not just passive observation in quantum mechanics: it determines which possible outcome becomes definite. This raises deep questions about randomness, reality, and what physical theories can predict.",
      "title": "Why quantum measurement changes the picture"
    },
    {
      "description": "Quantum rules explain chemical bonds, semiconductors, lasers, solar cells, and MRI scanners. Physicists, chemists, engineers, and computer scientists also use them to develop quantum sensors, secure communication, and quantum computers.",
      "title": "How quantum mechanics powers technology"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Civil procedure is the framework courts use to handle disputes—from choosing the right court and notifying the defendant to gathering evidence, holding a trial, and enforcing a judgment. It shapes whether legal rights can be pursued fairly and effectively.",
    "title": "How Civil Lawsuits Work"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Civil procedure answers practical questions about lawsuits: Who may sue, where can a case be heard, what must each side disclose, and when may a judge resolve the dispute without a trial?",
      "title": "What Civil Procedure Controls"
    },
    {
      "description": "A court needs authority over the dispute and the parties before it can act. Jurisdiction and venue can affect convenience, strategy, applicable law, and whether a judgment will be valid.",
      "title": "Why Jurisdiction and Venue Matter"
    },
    {
      "description": "A civil case usually moves through pleadings, information gathering, motions, possible settlement, trial, and appeal. Many cases end before trial because the rules create several earlier paths to resolution.",
      "title": "How a Civil Lawsuit Moves Through Court"
    },
    {
      "description": "Deadlines, notice, access to evidence, and opportunities to respond can determine whether a process is fair. Civil procedure balances accuracy and participation against cost, delay, and efficient use of courts.",
      "title": "How Civil Procedure Shapes Fairness"
    },
    {
      "description": "Litigators, judges, court clerks, mediators, paralegals, legal-aid teams, and policymakers all work with civil procedure. Their work includes drafting filings, managing cases, negotiating settlements, improving court access, and designing better dispute systems.",
      "title": "Who Uses Civil Procedure and Why"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Una mirada a cómo las calles, viviendas, parques, transportes y reglas urbanas moldean la vida diaria, y a las personas que trabajan para crear ciudades más habitables, conectadas y justas.",
    "title": "Cómo el urbanismo da forma a las ciudades"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "El urbanismo estudia cómo se ocupa, conecta y transforma el territorio. Reúne vivienda, movilidad, servicios, espacio público y ambiente para responder una pregunta concreta: ¿cómo queremos vivir juntos?",
      "title": "Qué organiza el urbanismo en una ciudad"
    },
    {
      "description": "La ubicación de una vivienda, una escuela o una parada de autobús cambia tiempos, costos y oportunidades. La densidad y la mezcla de usos pueden acercar actividades, mientras que la expansión urbana suele aumentar distancias.",
      "title": "Cómo el urbanismo acerca vivienda, empleo y servicios"
    },
    {
      "description": "Una calle no solo mueve automóviles: también permite caminar, comerciar, jugar, encontrarse y descansar. Decisiones pequeñas —como ampliar una acera o crear un carril exclusivo— pueden transformar todo un barrio.",
      "title": "Por qué las calles son clave para el urbanismo"
    },
    {
      "description": "Construir más viviendas, proteger áreas naturales o mejorar el transporte implica intereses y necesidades distintas. El urbanismo usa mapas, datos, normas y participación vecinal para evaluar opciones y sus consecuencias.",
      "title": "Cómo el urbanismo decide entre necesidades urbanas"
    },
    {
      "description": "Urbanistas, arquitectos, ingenieros, geógrafos, especialistas en transporte y organizaciones comunitarias colaboran en planes barriales, ciclovías, parques, vivienda, recuperación de centros y adaptación climática.",
      "title": "Quiénes convierten planes urbanos en ciudades reales"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "L’histoire de l’art relie les œuvres aux sociétés qui les ont produites. Images, monuments et objets révèlent des croyances, des pouvoirs, des techniques et des façons de voir le monde.",
    "title": "L’histoire de l’art : voir les œuvres autrement"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "L’histoire de l’art étudie bien plus que la peinture : sculptures, bâtiments, photographies, affiches, textiles, films et objets du quotidien deviennent des traces à interroger.",
      "title": "Ce que l’histoire de l’art étudie"
    },
    {
      "description": "Une œuvre porte les marques de son contexte : matériaux disponibles, croyances, commandes, conflits ou innovations. Même un portrait peut parler de statut social et de pouvoir.",
      "title": "Comment l’art raconte une époque"
    },
    {
      "description": "Composition, couleur, lumière, gestes et symboles orientent le regard. Observer ces choix permet de poser des questions précises sans réduire une œuvre à « j’aime » ou « je n’aime pas ».",
      "title": "Comment l’histoire de l’art fait parler les images"
    },
    {
      "description": "Les styles circulent entre cultures, tandis que les artistes empruntent, transforment ou contestent des formes anciennes. Une même image peut ainsi cacher plusieurs héritages.",
      "title": "Pourquoi les formes artistiques voyagent et changent"
    },
    {
      "description": "Musées, archives, fouilles, restauration, médiation et recherche mobilisent l’histoire de l’art. Elle sert aussi à documenter le patrimoine, préparer une exposition ou enquêter sur l’origine d’un objet.",
      "title": "Les métiers et projets liés à l’histoire de l’art"
    }
  ]
}
